 Short answer: quite a few. The architecture is already capable, but we’re missing convenience layers Laravel gives by default.

  Highest-value niceties we could add now:

  1. FormRequest-style request objects
     Route schema + parsed/validated input object passed to controller, so controllers don’t touch raw request.body/query everywh
     ere.
  2. First-class domain error classes + automatic HTTP mapping
     One standard DomainError family (Validation, Conflict, NotFound) mapped globally to status + payload shape, instead of per-
     controller mapping.
  3. Controller/action autowiring by class token
     If constructor deps are registered, instantiate automatically. Reduces repetitive provider wiring noise.
  4. Named middleware aliases + groups
     auth, throttle, csrf, owner aliases and route groups like Laravel middleware groups.
  5. Route-level policy DSL
     Simple declarative policy fields (auth, permission, rateLimit) enforced uniformly, not ad-hoc.
  6. Built-in CRUD scaffolding generators
     Generate provider/controller/action/service/repository/schema/tests with one command.
  7. Route model/repository binding
     Route params resolve to entities/repo lookups automatically with consistent 404 behavior.
  8. Standard test harness for 3 layers
     Out-of-the-box helpers for service unit, controller, and route/provider integration tests.
  9. Typed module config contract
     Per-module config schema + startup validation, so env/config errors fail fast and clearly.
  10. Automatic request scope context
     Create scoped container per request with request-id/user/context already injected.
  11. Resource API helpers with conventions
     You have resource/apiResource; add conventions for schemas, errors, pagination, and policies so it’s truly plug-and-play.
  12. Opinionated docs-to-code templates
     Every manual chapter example should be generated/runnable package by default (you’re already pushing this in the right
     direction).

  If you want the “no good reason we don’t have it” shortlist, it’s really: 1, 2, 4, 6, 8. Those are mostly productization work,
  not hard architecture work.


› We have 5 and 6, just not ported yet. tests will come later. for the rest... which one of these are possible and actually kind
  of easy to achieve?


• Given what already exists in JSKIT today, these are the easiest wins:

  1. DomainError + global HTTP mapping (easy)
     You already have AppError and now BaseController. Add a small domain error family and one mapper so controllers/actions stop
     repeating status logic.
  2. Middleware aliases/groups (easy)
     HTTP runtime already supports middleware stacks and route policy config. Add alias/group expansion (auth, throttle, csrf,
     etc.) before registration.
  3. Request-scope container per request (easy-medium)
     app.createScope(...) already exists. Wrap route execution so each request gets a scope/context token automatically.
  4. Typed module config helper (easy-medium)
     Add a kernel helper to validate module/provider config with TypeBox at boot (defineModuleConfig(schema, raw) style). Fast
     fail, better DX.
  5. FormRequest-lite (medium)
     Not full Laravel magic, but easy to add a helper that returns validated input (body/query/params) so controllers don’t touch
     raw request shape.



     